<subSubSection id="7A1006E3DA903C0EC23400060B594293" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="description">
<paragraph id="B3CD765AFC4A0F741DF29F26768173B2" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0289E55B957599A0CD8A58BB82B4F103" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="14" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
Small to large 
<emphasis id="5D956C1248A368B63E81D9EED0022EAE" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">trees</emphasis>
(rarely shrubby and broadly branching), usually hermaphroditic (except 
<taxonomicName id="52F68684B63E23C130B4570F7E7845F4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="C9007B441EA647C368F5F4D0B63FE808" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Simple, thick plank buttresses to 100 cm high sometimes present. 
<emphasis id="419B9C5642D21A9129FECD7549B0BFDA" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Outer bark</emphasis>
brown or usually gray, densely to broadly fissured, sometimes thick, usually rough, often with raised lenticels, rarely (some 
<taxonomicName id="C88A2CD9B6CC10A6E2B34A72B21815A5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias mombin" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mombin">
<emphasis id="D468F2F1F8C9AC04AA997A752B66BF72" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias mombin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F74C7ECC66FA128C00CD647814FEFA5C" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="0DB96A970B7E601072158F5C252616BF" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with large, corky, tooth-like projections. 
<emphasis id="858C6709EDDB7F9589DFE367A4C94466" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Inner bark</emphasis>
usually broadly striate (white and rose, red, orange, or brown). 
<taxonomicName id="33C74E5FA6679BEACDEBC7E190D98E37" genus="Resin" lsidName="Resin" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6A4338D4459E17FC9A5A07D0A785610C" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Resin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
viscous and usually clear or less often cloudy (
<taxonomicName id="72A86ADB1F6EEF99F2751078EFF07F73" authorityName="J. D. Mitch. &amp; Daly" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias globosa" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="globosa">
<emphasis id="20883B77BA8861365AFB418989F729A6" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias globosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<emphasis id="2F4470C1D3A096A86FD5C4ACC9529C26" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Trichomes</emphasis>
of various simple hairs and capitate glandular hairs. 
<emphasis id="374E2082CA0746647D0AB69819FC7970" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Leaves</emphasis>
alternate, aggregated toward branch tips, sometimes deciduous (sometimes facultatively so), usually imparipinnate, petiolulate; leaflets (sub)opposite, the apex often apiculate; margin entire/cren(ul)ate/serr(ul)ate (Figs 
<figureCitation id="612086404F910C4D7762B7D6FD8D37D6" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leaflets of Spondias species, showing details of the margin (insets): Spondias dulcis (Ayala &amp; Criollo 3982, NY); Spondias macrocarpa (Thomas et al. 6823, NY); Spondias mombin (Acevedo 6037, NY); Spondias globosa (Neill &amp; Palacios 7079, NY); Spondias radlkoferi narrow-leaflet form (Crane 458, LL) and broad-leaflet form (Contreras 6976, LL); Spondias purpurea (Grijalva 770, NY); Spondias testudinis (Lao Magin 112, NY); Spondias tuberosa (Carvalho et al. 3767, NY); Spondias venulosa (Stehmann 20855, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">2</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation id="A59E7B6EB99E3CA796A30E654DB48AA1" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figure 4. Leaf architecture of Spondias purpurea (contd.). A Tooth B Intersecondary vein C Irregularly spaced, arcuate secondaries. (from Madsen 63428, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">4</figureCitation>
), the sinuses often glandular; intramarginal vein present (see Figs 
<figureCitation id="5D40EE7B57ED25C7204B4759B3D6D6B9" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Leaf architecture of Spondias globosa. A Intramarginal vein B Secondary vein course straight C Composite admedial tertiary vein branching from intramarginal (defined by box) (from Vasquez 12866, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">1</figureCitation>
- 
<figureCitation id="CFCFE16B3F712A163B26896C08816F01" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figure 10. Leaf architecture of Spondias globosa (contd.). A Intramarginal vein B Incompletely looped marginal ultimate venation. (from Nelson 786, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">10</figureCitation>
for leaflet venation); intercostal tertiaries usually irregular-reticulate and often branching admedially, areoles often poorly developed; freely ending veinlets dendritic, often highly branched, leaflets often glandular-punctate. 
<emphasis id="F50846AEB1E2F2E9550C2DAB16AD2529" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Inflorescences</emphasis>
produced either before leaf flush (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="00D170F9612B56B2AEC6F067973ECF0E" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="6AB40CDB68CF28BBB4512D7E73B98B31" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or during leaf flush, terminal or axillary, paniculate (reduced to a pseudoracemose botryoid in 
<taxonomicName id="4C15CC598B4C96E556445CA13761F06F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="C8FC3CDCDD3108B7A603DCE6CBA99F66" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="BA9594A8D83C21375C14DE9A1455027B" author="Barfod, A" journalOrPublisher="Nordic Journal of Botany" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="3 - 11" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1756-1051.1988.tb01699.x" refId="B12" refString="Barfod, A, 1988. Inflorescence morphology of some South American Anacardiaceae and the possible phylogenetic trends. Nordic Journal of Botany 8: 3 - 11, DOI: 10.1111/j.1756-1051.1988.tb01699.x" title="Inflorescence morphology of some South American Anacardiaceae and the possible phylogenetic trends." url="10.1111/j.1756-1051.1988.tb01699.x" volume="8" year="1988">Barfod 1988</bibRefCitation>
); inflorescence bracts subtending secondary axes early-caducous; pedicel articulated. 
<emphasis id="DEE67C8E44B9F155C973E570A099BB7D" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Flowers</emphasis>
usually hermaphroditic but strongly protandrous (dioecious in 
<taxonomicName id="F1753679CC21F3DA570FDA9280F78473" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="EF726A1304A3D3F468EA01C8B448EC3A" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="830AB676FC8E6D205D8B9343C078C366" captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Flowers of Spondias purpurea. A Staminate flower at anthesis (left), and same with corolla removed B Disk, staminode, and stamen C Pistillate flower at anthesis (left), and same in longisection through center plus articulated pedicel. A-B from Sidwell et al. 589 (NY) C from Daly 137 (NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">14</figureCitation>
), pentamerous, calyx green (often red in 
<taxonomicName id="3F1F8833C1F9AAB37630328201CF54B1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="BA7B3F3CACE89E6AA78CF1CC1B9DBBB2" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), shorter than the disk, lobes usually apert (quincuncial at the base and valvate at the apex where they meet in 
<taxonomicName id="75509B77A27398EE35DBCF985246EF36" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="CB4BF48097AFC1AA090287476CA7638F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1C93FA9BD47827AA9C13BEC476E8AA58" author="Bachelier, JB" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linaean Society" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="499 - 571" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1095-8339.2009.00959.x" refId="B9" refString="Bachelier, JB, Endress, PK, 2009. Comparative floral morphology and anatomy of Anacardiaceae and Burseraceae (Sapindales), with a special focus on gynoecium structure and evolution. Botanical Journal of the Linaean Society 159: 499 - 571, DOI: 10.1111/j.1095-8339.2009.00959.x" title="Comparative floral morphology and anatomy of Anacardiaceae and Burseraceae (Sapindales), with a special focus on gynoecium structure and evolution." url="10.1111/j.1095-8339.2009.00959.x" volume="159" year="2009">Bachelier and Endress 2009</bibRefCitation>
); corolla valvate, petals yellowishwhite (usually red in 
<taxonomicName id="343EF4C4AC42ED71BCE9E5C13A719412" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="E7B782263029DAE115C9C692DA122758" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); patent or strongly reflexed at anthesis (spreading in 
<taxonomicName id="315CCB06509A23B95BFF9CF388CE8632" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="66A2604A64760B4B6F2CF5D253D7551D" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), often terminating in a swollen and strongly inflexed apiculum, the margin papillate; stamens (8)10, in two unequal series, outer series opposite the carpels, filaments linear to subulate, glabrous, anthers dorsifixed, yellow; disk intrastaminal, annular, summit and outer margin variously shaped (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CAB1F1455E53AD7F8F72EE737495D553" captionStart="Figure 15" captionStartId="F15" captionText="Figure 15. Flowers of Spondias species: Spondias dulcis (Wurdack 315, NY); Spondias macrocarpa (Spada 013 / 77, NY); Spondias globosa (Daly et al. 7836, NY); Spondias radlkoferi (Heithaus 119, NY); Spondias testudinis (Lao Magin 112, NY); Spondias tuberosa (Carauta 552, NY); Spondias venulosa (Queiroz 2604, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">15</figureCitation>
), usually yellow or less often pink (some 
<taxonomicName id="2A73E6FC1234D47D96D2FC2A4105CE80" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="E06F0A5DDAE23C6931CFBD77B0658C54" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or purple (some 
<taxonomicName id="4FE9052FEBCA5509266E7E3EF609C325" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias radlkoferi" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="radlkoferi">
<emphasis id="ABE7CA9D35FB978C30AF07A8EFCE58BD" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias radlkoferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); pistillode (
<taxonomicName id="2BC7025C7DE0C64C74891E1237F1BCF5" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="9F821FC2E54EE7779F2E41D4E535E4D6" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only) reduced to 3-5 subulate styles; at anthesis the ovary usually rudimentary, developing after the anthers dehisce (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E338DEF3E60B65E1102B03DE01B99DE9" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Flowers of Spondias mombin. A Opening bud B Flower at anthesis (top) and longisection at center of same C Flower post-anthesis with pistil further developed (top), longisection at center of same (bottom), and disk and pistil. A-C from Rusby &amp; Squires 102 (NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">11</figureCitation>
), pistil (3-) 5locular, surmounted by (3-)5 short, free styles (
<taxonomicName id="11E77C8BB6D4ED70B2158037BCD688FF" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="5459C8B6A5085207ECC52F1B6A3E8B73" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or usually the styles (broadly) subulate and separate at least half the length of the pistil, connivent at least basally, stigmas usually extrorse (introrse in 
<taxonomicName id="218417C419285355BC595A7100516B3F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="8D3F81329AD9F842C31048C38FC5F6EF" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DD5265751B2641BFFE33D5FD9D643AFB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias radlkoferi" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="radlkoferi">
<emphasis id="709F89D24F7077AABDF717517A559484" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias radlkoferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), discoid to linear; each locule with one apical ovule, the ovules crassinucellar and bitegmic, styles separating as fruit develops. 
<emphasis id="995758EFABEF6AEA91F5E9DA73541F0F" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fruit</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4BC15545EB150C93518F6DE5EC152C6F" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="F16" captionText="Figure 16. Fruits of Neotropical Spondias. Spondias dulcis (dry fruit: Berlin 870, NY; and longisection: unvouchered photo), Spondias macrocarpa (dry fruit: Thomas et al. 6823, NY), Spondias expeditionaria (endocarp and fresh fruit: Lorenzi s. n., NY), Spondias mombin (dry fruit: Mostacedo 2941, NY; endocarp: Moraes 1046, NY), Spondias globosa (fresh fruit [top], dry fruit, and endocarp: Daly et al. 8472, NY), Spondias purpurea (fresh fruit: unvouchered photo; dry fruit: Moreno 2827, NY; endocarp: Magallanes 3887), Spondias admirabilis (dry fruit: Farney et al. 4046, NY), Spondias radlkoferi (dry fruit: Nee 6729, NY; endocarp: Moran 6291, NY), Spondias testudinis (fresh and dry fruit; Daly et al. 7559, NY), Spondias tuberosa (fresh fruit: from Morton, 1987; dry fruit: Mattos Silva 2299, NY), and Spondias venulosa (fresh fruit: from photo in Lorenzi, 1998; dry fruit: Araujo 7828, NY)." pageId="12" pageNumber="13">16</figureCitation>
) a (1) 3-5-seeded, green, yellow, orange, or red drupe, oblong, (depressed-)globose, obovoid, or ellipsoid, remnants of styles widely separated and often visible in developing fruits; exocarp usually smooth (densely lenticellate in 
<taxonomicName id="C7EB6EBFBFD7B6902CDFF1BD19EC91A1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias testudinis" order="Sapindales" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="testudinis">
<emphasis id="27173404C0579D755192D2F42E7DD520" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Spondias testudinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); mesocarp fleshy, edible, sweet and sour, endocarp bony and enveloped by a fibrous matrix (with spiny projections and growing over apex of pedicel 
<pageBreakToken id="0D30EDC68C5EE447C6B92F909650D9F6" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" start="start">in</pageBreakToken>
<taxonomicName id="AE076C68CC6686AA57C383924F095C28" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias dulcis" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcis">
<emphasis id="2C51ED845A03DC7126D2DFF8CCCC5B0A" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias dulcis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), at maturity the fruit often breaking away at articulation of pedicel. 
<emphasis id="C4A0AE3766A899B5B8BFEA31A6DFE10A" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Pollen</emphasis>
(based on 
<bibRefCitation id="5D140AC0545C1E9D7C1C6A12A63FA808" author="Roubik, DW" journalOrPublisher="Louis," pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="1 - 268" refId="B153" refString="Roubik, DW, Moreno, PJE, 1991. Pollen and Spores of Barro Colorado Island. Monographs in Systematic Botany. Missouri Botanical Garden, St. Louis, 36: 1 - 268" title="Pollen and Spores of Barro Colorado Island. Monographs in Systematic Botany. Missouri Botanical Garden, St." volume="36" year="1991">Roubik and Moreno P. 1991</bibRefCitation>
): 41-56 
<normalizedToken id="B0C98576E1DA46BDF3EA44C9D2E05990" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
22-44 
<normalizedToken id="61F93E251AD09BB0A572EDAB74CAD14A" originalValue="µ">µ</normalizedToken>
, prolate or subprolate, pores 6-15 
<normalizedToken id="92EA50E070D84B9DDDABE25A37A061AF" originalValue="µ">µ</normalizedToken>
diam. 
<emphasis id="5AFE292AC52D2850232E3874D18C34F0" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Seedlings</emphasis>
: germination hypogeal, tap root and hypocotyl emerge from blunt end of fruit; hypocotyl emerges, curved at first, then carries cotyledons aloft; phanerocotylar; cotyledons opposite, linear, green, sessile, somewhat fleshy; first eophylls opposite and imparipinnate (
<taxonomicName id="C4F79F5CCEAD8E93C19D2E15B0A1C453" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias testudinis" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="testudinis">
<emphasis id="AABAAACA69E1A9DD37478D2CC36F3B1A" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias testudinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Fig. 
<figureCitation id="CB58FE4BE1E6C0810FA206A28C67B93E" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F17" captionText="Figure 17. Spondias testudinis. A Branchlet B Detail of leaflet blade and margin C Inflorescence D Bud E Flower at anthesis F Longisection through same at center G Fresh fruit H Seedling. A, B from Lao Magin 112 (NY) C-F from Lao Magin 83 (NY) G from specimen and field photo of Daly et al. 7559 (NY) H from specimen and field photo of Daly et al. 7251 (NY)." pageId="13" pageNumber="14">17H</figureCitation>
) or trifoliolate (pers. obs., 
<bibRefCitation id="F9426CF042D17F70113C0C3BE493B34A" author="Vogel, EF" journalOrPublisher="Centre for Agricultural Publishing and Documentation, Wageningen" pageId="66" pageNumber="67" refId="B176" refString="Vogel, EF, 1980. Seedlings of Dicotyledons. Centre for Agricultural Publishing and Documentation, Wageningen" title="Seedlings of Dicotyledons" year="1980">Vogel 1980</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="6A3E23DE26E62DBB0F37781827B07AC8" author="Garwood, NC" journalOrPublisher="Comstock Publishing Associates, Ithaca" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" refId="B57" refString="Garwood, NC, 2009. Seedlings of Barro Colorado Island and the Neotropics. Comstock Publishing Associates, Ithaca" title="Seedlings of Barro Colorado Island and the Neotropics" year="2009">Garwood 2009</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="17F7616F87F2CD0F99974EB665EECF86" genus="Chromosomes" lsidName="Chromosomes" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0CA99559A3802DDAE195D95254320515" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Chromosomes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: n = 16, 2n = 32 (
<bibRefCitation id="D003CC73245A45C882C86057C21AE0E9" author="Simmonds, NW" journalOrPublisher="Heredity" pageId="65" pageNumber="66" pagination="139 - 146" publicationUrl="10.1038/hdy.1954.11" refId="B159" refString="Simmonds, NW, 1954. Chromosome behavior in some tropical plants. Heredity 8: 139 - 146, DOI: 10.1038/hdy.1954.11" title="Chromosome behavior in some tropical plants." url="10.1038/hdy.1954.11" volume="8" year="1954">Simmonds 1954</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="11FF093FC9EB52F823D68E57E970EA41" author="Bawa, KS" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Arnold Arboretum" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="422 - 434" refId="B14" refString="Bawa, KS, 1973. Chromosome numbers of tree species of a lowland tropical community. Journal of the Arnold Arboretum 54: 422 - 434" title="Chromosome numbers of tree species of a lowland tropical community." volume="54" year="1973">Bawa 1973</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1CB17BBC5B891EE23F398593B8CE9F5E" author="Mehra, PN" journalOrPublisher="Sree Saraswaty Press, Calcutta" pageId="63" pageNumber="64" refId="B113" refString="Mehra, PN, 1976. Cytology of Himalayan Hardwoods. Sree Saraswaty Press, Calcutta" title="Cytology of Himalayan Hardwoods" year="1976">Mehra 1976</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="5D0CAA18F040DD520FC7E92EC25B718D" author="Guerra, MS" journalOrPublisher="Revista Brasileira de Genetica" pageId="60" pageNumber="61" pagination="21 - 40" refId="B63" refString="Guerra, MS, 1986. Citogenetica de angiospermas coletadas em Pernambuco. I. Revista Brasileira de Genetica 9: 21 - 40" title="Citogenetica de angiospermas coletadas em Pernambuco. I." volume="9" year="1986">Guerra 1986</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="75B11FAA5B26379AADFDDEEC18BDBD64" author="Pedrosa, A" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Brasilica" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="49 - 60" refId="B140" refString="Pedrosa, A, Gitai, J, Barros e Silva, AE, Felix, LP, Guerra, M, 1999. Citogenetica de angiospermas coletadas em Pernambuco V. Acta Botanica Brasilica 13: 49 - 60" title="Citogenetica de angiospermas coletadas em Pernambuco V." volume="13" year="1999">Pedrosa et al. 1999</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="1A51ED7BF1A17D638ECBA70D33318DCD" author="Almeida, CCS" journalOrPublisher="Botanical Journal of the Linnaean Society" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="541 - 547" publicationUrl="10.1111/j.1095-8339.2007.00721.x" refId="B4" refString="Almeida, CCS, Carvalho, PCL, Guerra, M, 2007. Karyotype differentiation among Spondias species and the putative hybrid Umbu-caja (Anacardiaceae). Botanical Journal of the Linnaean Society 155: 541 - 547, DOI: 10.1111/j.1095-8339.2007.00721.x" title="Karyotype differentiation among Spondias species and the putative hybrid Umbu-caja (Anacardiaceae)." url="10.1111/j.1095-8339.2007.00721.x" volume="155" year="2007">Almeida et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AAB05019C2E5CED92B50F6E79F0BD2AB" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Of the ca. 18 species in 
<taxonomicName id="62ED64F70EF076708459E620A093D454" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="03E7F07BE3997402C14CDEB10FB26290" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, ten are native to the New World, distributed from Mexico to southern Brazil, one is native to Madagascar, and seven are native to Asia and the South Pacific, from Malesia (sensu 
<emphasis id="FADEEE99B9FA8F2AA531DE4EC1024F3E" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Flora Malesiana</emphasis>
) to tropical China, Sri Lanka, Indochina, Thailand, India (except extreme north), Myanmar (Burma), Solomon Islands east to Polynesia. 
<taxonomicName id="48D322BE47F82AB01A32C13FF8E51163" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias dulcis" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dulcis">
<emphasis id="FA50B5FEA8B2A73C55E80E3433FD0F23" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias dulcis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is cultivated in tropical America and the Antilles; 
<taxonomicName id="362DC39DAF98E1422A038482CDE992C0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias mombin" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mombin">
<emphasis id="726204AE3D64C3E1C5D124D109882FF5" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias mombin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4CA2A8B8D5CBEFECAABCB9FDB464B91B" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="BCB2834F5BF022A1BF8129888DF1D0C2" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are both introduced throughout Tropical West Africa and Asia (and in the West Indies, where they are not found in primary vegetation and may not be native); 
<taxonomicName id="F6EA29005FA70EA5F715CB827E4DBC9F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias mombin" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mombin">
<emphasis id="F2403D6AA33B980FBED37BE90C836807" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias mombin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is often adventive in Tropical West Africa.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F6B38570814F9C4150C6FBA219F53C4" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
Some of the species native to the Neotropics have restricted distributions. 
<taxonomicName id="D4074211227B34CCE32BCEEE1F436184" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias testudinis" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="testudinis">
<emphasis id="1FFCFD7F9EE7A5F605E0A98F886F46EC" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias testudinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is restricted to southwestern Amazonia, and 
<taxonomicName id="3C8C2945475083DD43A3333367DEBACC" authorityName="J. D. Mitch. &amp; Daly" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias admirabilis" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="admirabilis">
<emphasis id="EB469AA212675253335B2F3B81099212" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias admirabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CDE8AEE8670BC00ACD0BD4923E7299AF" authorityName="J. D. Mitch. &amp; Daly" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias expeditionaria" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="expeditionaria">
<emphasis id="6DD8F6824FAA1C711B82C31827738C87" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias expeditionaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
both are known from very few localities in 
<normalizedToken id="A772F5B424F9662851201453BB16CFB1" originalValue="Brazil’s">Brazil's</normalizedToken>
Atlantic Coastal Forest, while the other two Atlantic Forest species, 
<taxonomicName id="D1E31F019801D8CA15A8A926ADB56DCD" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias macrocarpa" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="macrocarpa">
<emphasis id="E89F3C2ED558E6A50562B52784BF8226" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias macrocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and especially 
<taxonomicName id="3F408EF2537A616A3BDAB6A0460B696A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias venulosa" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="venulosa">
<emphasis id="038CEBF646C68F385F69D9B71D5ACA26" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias venulosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, are somewhat more broadly distributed in that region; both 
<taxonomicName id="0A328A01E871B9A88BB4BD72BA6559A7" authorityName="J. D. Mitch. &amp; Daly" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias expeditionaria" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="expeditionaria">
<emphasis id="89D0E8B4907247C9CCB9E15A9BAFFA16" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias expeditionaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="95D1CAE377598B4A558BC0F7962523BB" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias macrocarpa" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="macrocarpa">
<emphasis id="2708F2177587A19E437AEDC573C81DD4" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias macrocarpa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rare as well. The natural distribution of 
<taxonomicName id="C6888248F6DA1CBD7586ECA08C006731" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias tuberosa" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tuberosa">
<emphasis id="A5710BED0660CF08BC2DE3C3FFF1748A" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias tuberosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the arid 
<emphasis id="2D19526A800B99B2F1FCFA17965A32A7" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">caatinga</emphasis>
vegetation of Northeastern Brazil, and 
<taxonomicName id="05E8BA8AFCBCA1AF1A807728970422DD" authorityName="J. D. Mitch. &amp; Daly" authorityYear="2015" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias globosa" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="globosa">
<emphasis id="3587AA5FC198F8A90C37561ADDDBC51E" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias globosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a Western Amazon species. 
<taxonomicName id="4961C7ACE8830C9C9E6AC2BB0212EBB0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias radlkoferi" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="radlkoferi">
<emphasis id="0537E7682CF26A91E8251C7C5DB74C5A" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias radlkoferi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ranges from Mexico through Central America to Colombia and NW Venezuela; there is an unconfirmed report from Los 
<normalizedToken id="4DE7C528C4247AD5BC9871E04074E98E" originalValue="Ríos">Rios</normalizedToken>
in W Ecuador (Dodson 8837, MO). 
<taxonomicName id="63F3E0F846FE7AAA5803580BF7270DA2" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias purpurea" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="purpurea">
<emphasis id="D6AD7538A8C450682063646F87888AC1" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias purpurea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to N Mexico through Central America and may be native to SW Ecuador. 
<taxonomicName id="A923CC8918B78F8B4EBB39F12E5D7654" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Anacardiaceae" genus="Spondias" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Spondias mombin" order="Sapindales" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mombin">
<emphasis id="6019A1C4E82DC12D6020B157341FC364" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Spondias mombin</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is native to moist forests through much of northern South America, although it is uncertain whether the populations in 
<normalizedToken id="97B6113D9A190E5ACCF4C4A6C60E3C35" originalValue="Brazil’s">Brazil's</normalizedToken>
Atlantic Coastal Forest are native.
</paragraph>
